description:

The Cactus Channel and Chet Faker announce a 7inch two-track recording out September 18.

Funk/soul band, The Cactus Channel, have collaborated with ARIA Award winner Chet Faker for two tracks, ‘Kill the Doubt’ and ‘Sleeping Alone’ on a 7inch set for release via HopeStreet Recordings.

The recording, two years in the making, is a fine example of the depth of Melbourne’s music scene. It features Chet Faker’s seasoned songwriting with The Cactus Channel’s ear for musical instrumentation, resulting in a dose of classic soul and funk seen through a uniquely Melbourne perspective.

‘Kill The Doubt’ – The Cactus Channel feat. Chet Faker:
A side: Kill the Doubt
B side: Sleeping Alone

Amazon: http://goo.gl/ikeIrv
Enjoy! 

Press release:
I’m Not A Band’s newest single ’Cages’ is directly adressed to you – and your ego. The track is not about the suffering of locked up creatures, but a plea against emotional isolation. „We live in cages to never feel alone“, Simon sings in the very first line – and is referring to the good old principle of ’not caring, not being hurt’. But this is exactly what you should do. Care about others. When travelling. Partying. Or even in your relationships right now. Paradoxically, or also very fittingly, the sound of Cages transmits the feeling of holidays, adventures and new experiences. But there is always a little conflict – either in Simon’s voice or Stephan’s sometimes melancholic violin. 

Cages will be released on June 26, 2015, via AdP Records. Also on the Single are remixes by Frider Neumann, Christian Löffler, as well as ’Ocean Hearts’ – another song off of their latest album OCEANS.

title: S Strong & Boogie Belgique - Noir
description:
Exclusive download link coming soon, via Spinforth's Celebratory Centenary Scour #100, over at: ghettofunk.co.uk/category/scour

My latest collab with vintage fellow S Strong
Mastered by @funkanizer
Comments will be appreciated :)
Thanks for the support!

Promo blurb by Fat Harry: S Strong & Boogie Belgique get all flappy on our asses and all swingy on our balls. This tune was the B-Side to Balloo’s ‘Bear Necessites’ and follows on the story of the prickly pear, which turned out to be a peyote cactus. Feel the disturbing darkness build as Baloo’s trip turns a little sour as he slowly realises he’s a bear, he can sing and talk, he is alone and his massive cartoon paws are in fact massive cartoon paws. Mercifully the tune ends before he can viciously turn on Mowgli, his cartoon handlers are able to feed him more ketamine ants (you’re gonna love the way they tickle) to allow him to get through the scene with the dancing bananas and the singing monkeys. Phew!
